The location attribute indicates whether the alteration should appear to the left or the right of the preceding element. Its default value varies by element.

fields.name: root-alter
fields.description: The <root-alter> element represents the chromatic alteration of the root of the current chord within the <harmony> element. In some chord styles, the text for the <root-step> element may include <root-alter> information. In that case, the print-object attribute of the <root-alter> element can be set to no.

fields.name: numeral
fields.description: The <numeral> element represents the Roman numeral or Nashville number part of a harmony. It requires that the key be specified in the encoding, either with a <key> or <numeral-key> element.

fields.name: numeral-root
fields.description: The <numeral-root> element represents the Roman numeral or Nashville number as a positive integer from 1 to 7.

fields.name: numeral-key
fields.description: The <numeral-key> element is used when the key for the numeral is different than the key specified by the key signature.

fields.name: numeral-fifths
fields.description: The <numeral-fifths> element specifies the key in the same way as the <fifths> element.

fields.name: numeral-mode
fields.description: The <numeral-mode> specifies the scale that is used to interpret the <numeral-root> element values.

fields.name: style-text
fields.description: The style-text type represents a text element with a print-style attribute group.

fields.name: function
fields.description: The <function> element represents classical functional harmony with an indication like I, II, III rather than C, D, E. It represents the Roman numeral part of a functional harmony rather than the complete function itself. It has been deprecated as of MusicXML 4.0 in favor of the <numeral> element.

fields.name: kind
fields.description:
The <kind> element indicates the type of chord. The <degree> elements can then add, subtract, or alter from these starting points

The attributes are used to indicate the formatting of the symbol. Since the <kind> element is the constant in all the harmony-chord element groups that can make up a polychord, many formatting attributes are here. The alignment attributes are for the entire harmony-chord group of which this kind element is a part.

For the major-minor <kind>, only the minor symbol is used when use-symbols is yes. The major symbol is set using the symbol attribute in the <degree-value> element. The corresponding <degree-alter> value will usually be 0 in this case.

The text attribute may use strings such as "13sus" that refer to both the kind and one or more <degree> elements. In this case, the corresponding <degree> elements should have the print-object attribute set to no to keep redundant alterations from being displayed.

fields.name: inversion
fields.description: The <inversion> element represents harmony inversions. The value is a number indicating which inversion is used: 0 for root position, 1 for first inversion, etc.

fields.name: bass
fields.description: The <bass> element is used to indicate a bass note in popular music chord symbols, e.g. G/C. It is generally not used in functional harmony, as inversion is generally not used in pop chord symbols. As with <root>, it is divided into step and alter elements, similar to pitches.

fields.name: bass-separator
fields.description: The <bass-separator> element indicates that text, rather than a line or slash, separates the bass from what precedes it.

fields.name: bass-step
fields.description: The <bass-step> element represents the pitch step of the bass of the current chord within the harmony element.

fields.name: bass-alter
fields.description: The <bass-alter> element represents the chromatic alteration of the <bass> of the current chord within the <harmony> element. In some chord styles, the text for the <bass-step> element may include <bass-alter> information. In that case, the print-object attribute of the <bass-alter> element can be set to no.

fields.name: degree
fields.description:
The <degree> element is used to add, alter, or subtract individual notes in the chord. The print-object attribute can be used to keep the degree from printing separately when it has already taken into account in the text attribute of the <kind> element.

A harmony with a <kind> value of other can be spelled explicitly by using a series of <degree> elements together with a <root>, <numeral>, or <function> element.

fields.name: degree-value
fields.description: The content of the <degree-value> element is a number indicating the degree of the chord (1 for the root, 3 for third, etc).

fields.name: degree-alter
fields.description: The <degree-alter> element represents the chromatic alteration for the current degree. If the <degree-type> value is alter or subtract, the <degree-alter> value is relative to the degree already in the chord based on its kind element. If the <degree-type> value is add, the <degree-alter> is relative to a dominant chord (major and perfect intervals except for a minor seventh).

fields.name: degree-type
fields.description: The <degree-type> element indicates if this degree is an addition, alteration, or subtraction relative to the <kind> of the current chord. The value of the <degree-type> element affects the interpretation of the value of the <degree-alter> element.

fields.name: frame
fields.description: The frame type represents a frame or fretboard diagram used together with a chord symbol. The representation is based on the NIFF guitar grid with additional information. The frame type's unplayed attribute indicates what to display above a string that has no associated frame-note element. Typical values are x and the empty string. If the attribute is not present, the display of the unplayed string is application-defined.

fields.name: frame-strings
fields.description: The frame-strings element gives the overall size of the frame in vertical lines (strings).

fields.name: frame-frets
fields.description: The frame-frets element gives the overall size of the frame in horizontal spaces (frets).

fields.name: first-fret
fields.description: The <first-fret> element indicates which fret is shown in the top space of the frame; it is fret 1 if the element is not present.

fields.name: frame-note
fields.description: The frame-note type represents each note included in the frame. An open string will have a fret value of 0, while a muted string will not be associated with a frame-note element.

fields.name: barre
fields.description: The <barre> element indicates placing a finger over multiple strings on a single fret.

fields.name: figured-bass
fields.description: The <figured-bass> element represents figured bass notation. A <figured-bass> element takes its position from the first regular note (not a grace note or chord note) that follows in score order. The optional <duration> element is used to indicate changes of figures under a note. Figures are ordered from top to bottom.

fields.name: figure
fields.description: The <figure> element represents a single figure within a <figured-bass> element.

fields.name: prefix
fields.description: Values for the <prefix> element include plus and the accidental values sharp, flat, natural, double-sharp, flat-flat, and sharp-sharp. The <prefix> element may contain additional values for symbols specific to particular figured bass styles.

fields.name: figure-number
fields.description: A <figure-number> element represents a number. Overstrikes of the figure number are represented in the <suffix> element.

fields.name: suffix
fields.description: Values for the <suffix> element include plus and the accidental values sharp, flat, natural, double-sharp, flat-flat, and sharp-sharp. Suffixes include both symbols that come after the figure number and those that overstrike the figure number. The <suffix> values slash, back-slash, and vertical are used for slashed numbers indicating chromatic alteration. The orientation and display of the slash usually depends on the figure number. The <suffix> element may contain additional values for symbols specific to particular figured bass styles.

fields.name: print
fields.description:
The <print> element contains general printing parameters, including layout elements. The <part-name-display> and <part-abbreviation-display> elements may also be used here to change how a part name or abbreviation is displayed over the course of a piece. They take effect when the current measure or a succeeding measure starts a new system.

Layout group elements in a <print> element only apply to the current page, system, or staff. Music that follows continues to take the default values from the layout determined by the <defaults> element.

fields.name: measure-layout
fields.description: The <measure-layout> element includes the horizontal distance from the previous measure. It applies to the current measure only.

fields.name: measure-distance
fields.description: The <measure-distance> element specifies the horizontal distance from the previous measure. This value is only used for systems where there is horizontal whitespace in the middle of a system, as in systems with codas. To specify the measure width, use the width attribute of the <measure> element.

fields.name: measure-numbering
fields.description: The <measure-numbering> element describes how frequently measure numbers are displayed on this part. The text attribute from the <measure> element is used for display, or the number attribute if the text attribute is not present. Measures with an implicit attribute set to yes never display a measure number, regardless of the <measure-numbering> setting.

fields.name: barline
fields.description: If a barline is other than a normal single barline, it should be represented by a <barline> element that describes it. This includes information about repeats and multiple endings, as well as line style. Barline data is on the same level as the other musical data in a score - a child of a measure in a partwise score, or a part in a timewise score. This allows for barlines within measures, as in dotted barlines that subdivide measures in complex meters. The two <fermata> elements allow for fermatas on both sides of the barline (the lower one inverted).

fields.name: bar-style-color
fields.description: The <bar-style> element contains barline style and color information.

fields.name: ending
fields.description: The <ending> element represents multiple (e.g. first and second) endings. The element text is used when the text displayed in the ending is different than what appears in the number attribute.

fields.name: repeat
fields.description: The <repeat> element represents repeat marks.

fields.name: grouping
fields.description:
The <grouping> element is used for musical analysis. When the type attribute is start or single, it usually contains one or more <feature> elements.  Feature elements contained within a stop type of grouping may be ignored.

This element is flexible to allow for different types of analyses. Future versions of the MusicXML format may add elements that can represent more standardized categories of analysis data, allowing for easier data sharing.

fields.name: feature
fields.description: The <feature> element is a part of the <grouping> element used for musical analysis. The type attribute represents the type of the feature and the element content represents its value.

fields.name: score-timewise
fields.description: The <score-timewise> element is the root element for a timewise MusicXML score. It includes score header information followed by a series of <measure> elements with <part> elements inside.

fields.name: measure
fields.description: The <measure> element is the top level of musical organization below the <score-timewise> document element. It contains a sequence of <part> elements.

fields.name: part
fields.description: The <part> element includes the basic musical data such as <note>s within a <score-timewise> document.

fields.name: any
fields.description: The any element is used when a MusicXML ID refers to a single application or library sound ID, regardless of whether a solo or ensemble sound is used. The element content is the application or library sound ID.

fields.name: solo
fields.description: The solo and ensemble elements are used when an application has different IDs for solo and ensemble sounds, as represented by the solo and ensemble elements in a MusicXML score file. The solo element corresponds to the solo element in the MusicXML score file. The element content is the application or library sound ID.

fields.name: ensemble
fields.description: The solo and ensemble elements are used when an application has different IDs for solo and ensemble sounds, as represented by the solo and ensemble elements in a MusicXML score file. The ensemble element corresponds to the ensemble element in the MusicXML score file. The element content is the application or library sound ID.

fields.name: sound
fields.description:
The sound element lists one of the standard sounds available in MusicXML 4.0. The required id attribute lists the MusicXML sound identifier string used by the instrument-sound element.

The optional any, solo, and ensemble elements can be used for mapping MusicXML sound IDs to an application's or virtual instrument library's method of identifying sounds. These methods could include Sibelius SoundWorld IDs, capella genericsound IDs, and General MIDI patch numbers.

fields.name: sounds
fields.description:
Starting with Version 3.0, the MusicXML format includes a standard set of instrument sounds to identify musical timbres. These values are used in the instrument-sound element. The standard sounds are listed in the sounds.xml file included with MusicXML 4.0. The sounds element is the document element for this file. Applications may wish to provide a modified version of the sounds.xml file, where the element content includes an application's method for identifying sounds. Suggested use of the DTD: 
<!DOCTYPE sounds PUBLIC
    "-//Recordare//DTD MusicXML 4.0 Sounds//EN"
    "http://www.musicxml.org/dtds/sounds.dtd">
The XML catalog at catalog.xml supports validating against a local copy of the sounds.dtd file rather than the networked version in the system ID. Software often has trouble using system IDs due to factors such as restrictions on network access, or resources having moved from the original specified location.

fields.name: rootfile
fields.description: The rootfile element describes each top-level file in the MusicXML container. A MusicXML file used as a rootfile may have score-partwise, score-timewise, or opus as its document element.

fields.name: rootfiles
fields.description:
The rootfiles element includes the starting points for the different representations of a MusicXML score. The MusicXML root must be described in the first rootfile element. Additional rootfile elements can describe alternate versions such as PDF and audio files.
	
When a MusicXML file contains both a score file and separate files for individual parts, the score file is the one that is referenced in the first rootfile element. The part files can be linked from within the score file and need not be listed here.

fields.name: container
score
fields.description: The score elements provide the links to the individual scores within an opus.

fields.name: opus-link
fields.description: An opus-link provides a link to another opus document, allowing for multiple levels of opus collections via linking as well as nesting.

fields.name: title
fields.description: The title element specifies the title of an opus document.

fields.name: opus
fields.description: The opus element is the root element of a MusicXML opus. Each opus is made up of a series of score, opus-link, and/or nested opus elements. Future versions may include more metadata elements. In this version, we just include the title of the opus.

fields.name: formatted-text-footnote
fields.description: The <footnote> element specifies editorial information that appears in footnotes in the printed score.

fields.name: empty-placement-dot
fields.description: Empty placement variant used for dot elements.

fields.name: pull-off
fields.description: The <pull-off> element is used in guitar and fretted instrument notation. Since a single slur can be marked over many notes, the <pull-off> element is separate so the individual pair of notes can be specified. The element content can be used to specify how the <pull-off> should be notated. An empty element leaves this choice up to the application.

fields.name: toe
fields.description: The <toe> element is used with organ pedals.

fields.name: numeral-alter
fields.description: The <numeral-alter> element represents an alteration to the <numeral-root>, similar to the <alter> element for a <pitch>.

fields.name: link-attributes
fields.description: The link-attributes group includes all the simple XLink attributes supported in the MusicXML format. It is also used to connect a MusicXML score with MusicXML parts or a MusicXML opus.

fields.name: print-style-align
fields.description: The print-style-align attribute group adds the halign and valign attributes to the position, font, and color attributes.

fields.name: print-style
fields.description: The print-style attribute group collects the most popular combination of printing attributes: position, font, and color.

fields.name: position
fields.description: This is the position attribute group derived from the MusicXML schema. It uses the standard default-x positioning.

fields.name: font
fields.description: The font attribute group gathers together attributes for determining the font within a credit or direction. They are based on the text styles for Cascading Style Sheets. The font-family is a comma-separated list of font names. These can be specific font styles such as Maestro or Opus, or one of several generic font styles: music, engraved, handwritten, text, serif, sans-serif, handwritten, cursive, fantasy, and monospace. The music, engraved, and handwritten values refer to music fonts; the rest refer to text fonts. The fantasy style refers to decorative text such as found in older German-style printing. The font-style can be normal or italic. The font-size can be one of the CSS sizes (xx-small, x-small, small, medium, large, x-large, xx-large) or a numeric point size. The font-weight can be normal or bold. The default is application-dependent, but is a text font vs. a music font.

fields.name: color
fields.description: The color attribute group indicates the color of an element.

fields.name: halign
fields.description:
In cases where text extends over more than one line, horizontal alignment and justify values can be different. The most typical case is for credits, such as:

	Words and music by
	  Pat Songwriter

Typically this type of credit is aligned to the right, so that the position information refers to the right-most part of the text. But in this example, the text is center-justified, not right-justified.

The halign attribute is used in these situations. If it is not present, its value is the same as for the justify attribute. For elements where a justify attribute is not allowed, the default is implementation-dependent.

fields.name: valign
fields.description: The valign attribute is used to indicate vertical alignment to the top, middle, bottom, or baseline of the text. Defaults are implementation-dependent.

fields.name: element-position
fields.description: The element and position attributes are new as of Version 2.0. They allow for bookmarks and links to be positioned at higher resolution than the level of music-data elements. When no element and position attributes are present, the bookmark or link element refers to the next sibling element in the MusicXML file. The element attribute specifies an element type for a descendant of the next sibling element that is not a link or bookmark. The position attribute specifies the position of this descendant element, where the first position is 1. The position attribute is ignored if the element attribute is not present. For instance, an element value of "beam" and a position value of "2" defines the link or bookmark to refer to the second beam descendant of the next sibling element that is not a link or bookmark. This is equivalent to an XPath test of [.//beam[2]] done in the context of the sibling element.

fields.name: image-attributes
fields.description: The image-attributes group is used to include graphical images in a score. The required source attribute is the URL for the image file. The required type attribute is the MIME type for the image file format. Typical choices include application/postscript, image/gif, image/jpeg, image/png, and image/tiff. The optional height and width attributes are used to size and scale an image. The image should be scaled independently in X and Y if both height and width are specified. If only one attribute is specified, the image should be scaled proportionally to fit in the specified dimension.

fields.name: valign-image
fields.description: The valign-image attribute is used to indicate vertical alignment for images and graphics, so it removes the baseline value. Defaults are implementation-dependent.

fields.name: optional-unique-id
fields.description: The optional-unique-id attribute group allows an element to optionally specify an ID that is unique to the entire document. This attribute group is not used for a required id attribute, or for an id attribute that specifies an id reference.

fields.name: text-formatting-words
fields.description: The text-formatting attribute group collects the common formatting attributes for text elements. Default values may differ across the elements that use this group.

fields.name: justify
fields.description: The justify attribute is used to indicate left, center, or right justification. The default value varies for different elements. For elements where the justify attribute is present but the halign attribute is not, the justify attribute indicates horizontal alignment as well as justification.

fields.name: text-decoration
fields.description: The text-decoration attribute group is based on the similar feature in XHTML and CSS. It allows for text to be underlined, overlined, or struck-through. It extends the CSS version by allow double or triple lines instead of just being on or off.

fields.name: text-rotation
fields.description: The rotation attribute is used to rotate text around the alignment point specified by the halign and valign attributes. Positive values are clockwise rotations, while negative values are counter-clockwise rotations.

fields.name: letter-spacing
fields.description: The letter-spacing attribute specifies text tracking. Values are either "normal" or a number representing the number of ems to add between each letter. The number may be negative in order to subtract space. The default is normal, which allows flexibility of letter-spacing for purposes of text justification.

fields.name: line-height
fields.description: The line-height attribute specifies text leading. Values are either "normal" or a number representing the percentage of the current font height to use for leading. The default is "normal". The exact normal value is implementation-dependent, but values between 100 and 120 are recommended.

fields.name: text-direction
fields.description: The text-direction attribute is used to adjust and override the Unicode bidirectional text algorithm, similar to the W3C Internationalization Tag Set recommendation.

fields.name: enclosure
fields.description: The enclosure attribute group is used to specify the formatting of an enclosure around text or symbols.

fields.name: symbol-formatting
fields.description: The symbol-formatting attribute group collects the common formatting attributes for musical symbols. Default values may differ across the elements that use this group.

fields.name: group-name-text
fields.description: The group-name-text attribute group is used by the group-name and group-abbreviation elements. The print-style and justify attribute groups are deprecated in MusicXML 2.0 in favor of the new group-name-display and group-abbreviation-display elements.

fields.name: level-display
fields.description: The level-display attribute group specifies three common ways to indicate editorial indications: putting parentheses or square brackets around a symbol, or making the symbol a different size. If not specified, they are left to application defaults. It is used by the level and accidental elements.

fields.name: part-name-text
fields.description: The part-name-text attribute group is used by the part-name and part-abbreviation elements. The print-style and justify attribute groups are deprecated in MusicXML 2.0 in favor of the new part-name-display and part-abbreviation-display elements.

fields.name: placement
fields.description: The placement attribute indicates whether something is above or below another element, such as a note or a notation.

fields.name: position-note
fields.description:
The position attributes are based on MuseData print suggestions. For most elements, any program will compute a default x and y position. The position attributes let this be changed two ways.

The default-x and default-y attributes change the computation of the default position. For most elements, the origin is changed relative to the left-hand side of the note or the musical position within the bar (x) and the top line of the staff (y).

For the following elements, the default-x value changes the origin relative to the start of the current measure:

	- note
	- figured-bass
	- harmony
	- link
	- directive
	- measure-numbering
	- all descendants of the part-list element
	- all children of the direction-type element

This origin is from the start of the entire measure, at either the left barline or the start of the system.

When the default-x attribute is used within a child element of the part-name-display, part-abbreviation-display, group-name-display, or group-abbreviation-display elements, it changes the origin relative to the start of the first measure on the system. These values are used when the current measure or a succeeding measure starts a new system. The same change of origin is used for the group-symbol element.

For the note, figured-bass, and harmony elements, the default-x value is considered to have adjusted the musical position within the bar for its descendant elements.

Since the credit-words and credit-image elements are not related to a measure, in these cases the default-x and default-y attributes adjust the origin relative to the bottom left-hand corner of the specified page.

The relative-x and relative-y attributes change the position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-x and default-y attributes.

Positive x is right, negative x is left; positive y is up, negative y is down. All units are in tenths of interline space. For stems, positive relative-y lengthens a stem while negative relative-y shortens it.

The default-x and default-y position attributes provide higher-resolution positioning data than related features such as the placement attribute and the offset element. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both features should generally rely on the default-x and default-y attributes for their greater accuracy. For the relative-x and relative-y attributes, the offset element, placement attribute, and directive attribute provide context for the relative position information, so the two features should be interpreted together.

As elsewhere in the MusicXML format, tenths are the global tenths defined by the scaling element, not the local tenths of a staff resized by the staff-size element.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: The smufl attribute group is used to indicate a particular Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) character. Sometimes this is a formatting choice, and sometimes this is a refinement of the semantic meaning of an element.

fields.name: line-type
fields.description: The line-type attribute distinguishes between solid, dashed, dotted, and wavy lines.

fields.name: dashed-formatting
fields.description: The dashed-formatting entity represents the length of dashes and spaces in a dashed line. Both the dash-length and space-length attributes are represented in tenths. These attributes are ignored if the corresponding line-type attribute is not dashed.

fields.name: orientation
fields.description: The orientation attribute indicates whether slurs and ties are overhand (tips down) or underhand (tips up). This is distinct from the placement attribute used by any notation type.

fields.name: bezier
fields.description:
The bezier attribute group is used to indicate the curvature of slurs and ties, representing the control points for a cubic bezier curve. For ties, the bezier attribute group is used with the tied element.

Normal slurs, S-shaped slurs, and ties need only two bezier points: one associated with the start of the slur or tie, the other with the stop. Complex slurs and slurs divided over system breaks can specify additional bezier data at slur elements with a continue type.

The bezier-x, bezier-y, and bezier-offset attributes describe the outgoing bezier point for slurs and ties with a start type, and the incoming bezier point for slurs and ties with types of stop or continue. The bezier-x2, bezier-y2, and bezier-offset2 attributes are only valid with slurs of type continue, and describe the outgoing bezier point.

The bezier-x, bezier-y, bezier-x2, and bezier-y2 attributes are specified in tenths, relative to any position settings associated with the slur or tied element. The bezier-offset and bezier-offset2 attributes are measured in terms of musical divisions, like the offset element. 

The bezier-offset and bezier-offset2 attributes are deprecated as of MusicXML 3.1. If both the bezier-x and bezier-offset attributes are present, the bezier-x attribute takes priority. Similarly, the bezier-x2 attribute takes priority over the bezier-offset2 attribute. The two types of bezier attributes are not additive.

fields.name: line-shape
fields.description: The line-shape attribute distinguishes between straight and curved lines.

fields.name: bend-sound
fields.description:
The bend-sound type is used for bend and slide elements, and is similar to the trill-sound attribute group. Here the beats element refers to the number of discrete elements (like MIDI pitch bends) used to represent a continuous bend or slide. The first-beat indicates the percentage of the direction for starting a bend; the last-beat the percentage for ending it. The default choices are:

	accelerate = "no"
	beats = "4"
	first-beat = "25"
	last-beat = "75"

fields.name: trill-sound
fields.description:
The trill-sound attribute group includes attributes used to guide the sound of trills, mordents, turns, shakes, and wavy lines, based on MuseData sound suggestions. The default choices are:

	start-note = "upper"
	trill-step = "whole"
	two-note-turn = "none"
	accelerate = "no"
	beats = "4".

Second-beat and last-beat are percentages for landing on the indicated beat, with defaults of 25 and 75 respectively.

For mordent and inverted-mordent elements, the defaults are different:

	The default start-note is "main", not "upper".
	The default for beats is "3", not "4".
	The default for second-beat is "12", not "25".
	The default for last-beat is "24", not "75".

fields.name: line-length
fields.description: The line-length attribute distinguishes between different line lengths for doit, falloff, plop, and scoop articulations.

fields.name: position-music-data
fields.description: This variant of the position attribute group uses default-x positioning associated with music-data elements.

fields.name: printout
fields.description: The printout attribute group collects the different controls over printing an object (e.g. a note or rest) and its parts, including augmentation dots and lyrics. This is especially useful for notes that overlap in different voices, or for chord sheets that contain lyrics and chords but no melody.

fields.name: directive
fields.description: The directive attribute changes the default-x position of a direction. It indicates that the left-hand side of the direction is aligned with the left-hand side of the time signature. If no time signature is present, it is aligned with the left-hand side of the first music notational element in the measure. If a default-x, justify, or halign attribute is present, it overrides the directive attribute.

fields.name: system-relation
fields.description: The system-relation attribute group distinguishes elements that are associated with a system rather than the particular part where the element appears.

fields.name: print-attributes
fields.description:
The print-attributes group is used by the print element. The new-system and new-page attributes indicate whether to force a system or page break, or to force the current music onto the same system or page as the preceding music. Normally this is the first music data within a measure. If used in multi-part music, they should be placed in the same positions within each part, or the results are undefined. The page-number attribute sets the number of a new page; it is ignored if new-page is not "yes". Version 2.0 adds a blank-page attribute. This is a positive integer value that specifies the number of blank pages to insert before the current measure. It is ignored if new-page is not "yes". These blank pages have no music, but may have text or images specified by the credit element. This is used to allow a combination of pages that are all text, or all text and images, together with pages of music.

The staff-spacing attribute specifies spacing between multiple staves in tenths of staff space. This is deprecated as of Version 1.1; the staff-layout element should be used instead. If both are present, the staff-layout values take priority.

fields.name: measure-attributes
fields.description:
The measure-attributes group is used by the measure element. Measures have a required number attribute (going from partwise to timewise, measures are grouped via the number).

The implicit attribute is set to "yes" for measures where the measure number should never appear, such as pickup measures and the last half of mid-measure repeats. The value is "no" if not specified.

The non-controlling attribute is intended for use in multimetric music like the Don Giovanni minuet. If set to "yes", the left barline in this measure does not coincide with the left barline of measures in other parts. The value is "no" if not specified.

In partwise files, the number attribute should be the same for measures in different parts that share the same left barline. While the number attribute is often numeric, it does not have to be. Non-numeric values are typically used together with the implicit or non-controlling attributes being set to "yes". For a pickup measure, the number attribute is typically set to "0" and the implicit attribute is typically set to "yes". 

If measure numbers are not unique within a part, this can cause problems for conversions between partwise and timewise formats. The text attribute allows specification of displayed measure numbers that are different than what is used in the number attribute. This attribute is ignored for measures where the implicit attribute is set to "yes". Further details about measure numbering can be specified using the measure-numbering element.

Measure width is specified in tenths. These are the global tenths specified in the scaling element, not local tenths as modified by the staff-size element. The width covers the entire measure from barline or system start to barline or system end.

fields.name: part-attributes
fields.description: In either partwise or timewise format, the part element has an id attribute that is an IDREF back to a score-part in the part-list.

fields.name: document-attributes
fields.description: The document-attributes attribute group is used to specify the attributes for an entire MusicXML document. Currently this is used for the version attribute.

fields.name: opus-document-attributes
fields.description: The document-attributes attribute group is used to specify the attributes for an entire MusicXML document. Currently this is used for the version attribute.

fields.name: mordent-trill-sound
fields.description:
The trill-sound attribute group includes attributes used to guide the sound of trills, mordents, turns, shakes, and wavy lines, based on MuseData sound suggestions. The default choices are:

	start-note = "upper"
	trill-step = "whole"
	two-note-turn = "none"
	accelerate = "no"
	beats = "4".

Second-beat and last-beat are percentages for landing on the indicated beat, with defaults of 25 and 75 respectively.

For mordent and inverted-mordent elements, the defaults are different:

	The default start-note is "main", not "upper".
	The default for beats is "3", not "4".
	The default for second-beat is "12", not "25".
	The default for last-beat is "24", not "75".

fields.name: position-part-display
fields.description: This variant of the position attribute group uses default-x positioning associated with the display-text element. This may be duplicating the position-display attribute group.

fields.name: position-credit
fields.description: This variation of the position attribute group uses the credit-specific positioning for the default-x attribute.

fields.name: position-stem
fields.description: This variant of the position attribute group uses a relative-y definition specific to the stem element.

fields.name: print-style-music-data
fields.description: This variant of the print-style attribute group uses positioning associated with music-data elements.

fields.name: print-style-align-music-data
fields.description: This variant of the print-style-align attribute group uses positioning associated with music-data elements.

fields.name: print-style-credit
fields.description: This variant of the print-style attribute group uses credit-specific positioning.

fields.name: print-style-align-credit
fields.description: This variant of the print-style-align attribute group uses credit-specific positioning.

fields.name: position-display
fields.description: This variant of the position attribute group uses default-x positioning associated with the display-text element. This may be duplicating the position-part-display attribute group.

fields.name: position-footnote
fields.description: This variant of the position attribute uses default-x positioning specific to the footnote element.

fields.name: print-style-display
fields.description: This variant of the print-style attribute group uses positioning associated with the display-text element.

fields.name: print-style-footnote
fields.description: This variant of the print-style attribute group uses footnote-specific positioning.

fields.name: print-style-align-display
fields.description: This variant of the print-style-align attribute group uses positioning associated with the display-text element.

fields.name: print-style-align-footnote
fields.description: This variant of the print-style-align attribute group uses foonote-specific positioning.

fields.name: dashed-formatting-dashes
fields.description: Variation of dashed-formatting group for use with dashes element.

fields.name: type
fields.description: If yes, the absence of a particular element with a specified attribute or value is meaningful. It indicates that this information is not present in the score. If no, the absence is not meaningful because the encoding does not include this type of information.

fields.name: element
fields.description: Indicates the element that is supported or not by the encoding.

fields.name: attribute
fields.description: Indicates a specific element attribute that is supported or not by the encoding.

fields.name: value
fields.description: Indicates a specific attribute value that is supported or not by the encoding. Only used together with the attribute attribute.

fields.name: name
fields.description: Indicates the type of metadata the element content represents.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Specifies whether the margins apply to even pages, odd pages, or both. This attribute is not needed when used as part of a <print> element. The value is both if omitted when used in the <defaults> element.

fields.name: print-object
fields.description: Specifies whether or not to print an object. It is yes if not specified.

fields.name: default-x
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default horizontal position. The origin is changed relative to the left-hand side of the note or the musical position within the bar. Positive x is right and negative x is left.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the <offset> element. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both features should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: default-y
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default vertical position. The origin is changed relative to the top line of the staff. Positive y is up and negative y is down.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the placement attribute. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both attributes should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: relative-x
fields.description: Changes the horizontal position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-x attribute.  Positive x is right and negative x is left. It should be interpreted in the context of the <offset> element or directive attribute if those are present.

fields.name: relative-y
fields.description: Changes the vertical position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-y attribute. Positive y is up and negative y is down. It should be interpreted in the context of the placement attribute if that is present.

fields.name: font-family
fields.description: A comma-separated list of font names.

fields.name: font-style
fields.description: Normal or italic style.

fields.name: font-size
fields.description: One of the CSS sizes or a numeric point size.

fields.name: font-weight
fields.description: Normal or bold weight.

fields.name: color
fields.description: Indicates the color of an element.

fields.name: halign
fields.description:
In cases where text extends over more than one line, horizontal alignment and justify values can be different. The most typical case is for credits, such as: 
Words and music by
  Pat Songwriter
Typically this type of credit is aligned to the right, so that the position information refers to the right-most part of the text. But in this example, the text is center-justified, not right-justified. The halign attribute is used in these situations. If it is not present, its value is the same as for the justify attribute. For elements where a justify attribute is not allowed, the default is implementation-dependent.

fields.name: valign
fields.description: Indicates vertical alignment to the top, middle, bottom, or baseline of the text. The default is implementation-dependent.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Refers to staff numbers within the part, from top to bottom on the system. A value of 1 is used if not present.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The type of line whose width is being defined.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The type of note size being defined.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The type of distance being defined.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The type of glyph that is being defined.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The appearance type being specified.

fields.name: number
fields.description: The lyric number for which this is the default, corresponding to the number attribute in the <lyric> element.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The lyric name for which this is the default, corresponding to the name attribute in the <lyric> element.

fields.name: number
fields.description: The lyric number for which this is the default, corresponding to the number attribute in the <lyric> element.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The lyric name for which this is the default, corresponding to the name attribute in the <lyric> element.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The name of this link.

fields.name: element
fields.description: The element attribute specifies an element type for a descendant of the next sibling element that is not a <link> or <bookmark> element. When not present, the <bookmark> or <link> element refers to the next sibling element in the MusicXML file.

fields.name: position
fields.description:
The position attribute specifies the position of the descendant element specified by the element attribute, where the first position is 1. The position attribute is ignored if the element attribute is not present.

For instance, an element value of "beam" and a position value of "2" defines the <link> or <bookmark> to refer to the second beam descendant of the next sibling element that is not a <link> or <bookmark> element. This is equivalent to an XPath test of [.//beam[2]] done in the context of the sibling element.

fields.name: id
fields.description: The identifier for this bookmark, unique within this document.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The name for this bookmark.

fields.name: source
fields.description: The URL for the image file.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The MIME type for the image file format. Typical choices include application/postscript, image/gif, image/jpeg, image/png, and image/tiff.

fields.name: height
fields.description: Used to size and scale an image. The image should be scaled independently in X and Y if both height and width are specified. If only height is specified, the image should be scaled proportionally to fit in the specified Y dimension.

fields.name: width
fields.description: Used to size and scale an image. The image should be scaled independently in X and Y if both height and width are specified. If only width is specified, the image should be scaled proportionally to fit in the specified X dimension.

fields.name: valign
fields.description: Indicates vertical alignment to the top, middle, or bottom of the image. The default is implementation-dependent.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Specifies an ID that is unique to the entire document.

fields.name: justify
fields.description: Indicates left, center, or right justification. The default value varies for different elements. For elements where the justify attribute is present but the halign attribute is not, the justify attribute indicates horizontal alignment as well as justification.

fields.name: underline
fields.description: Number of lines to use when underlining text.

fields.name: overline
fields.description: Number of lines to use when overlining text.

fields.name: line-through
fields.description: Number of lines to use when striking through text.

fields.name: rotation
fields.description: Used to rotate text around the alignment point specified by the halign and valign attributes. Positive values are clockwise rotations, while negative values are counter-clockwise rotations.

fields.name: letter-spacing
fields.description: Specifies text tracking. Values are either normal, which allows flexibility of letter-spacing for purposes of text justification. or a number representing the number of ems to add between each letter. The number may be negative in order to subtract space. The value is normal if not specified.

fields.name: line-height
fields.description: Specifies text leading. Values are either normal or a number representing the percentage of the current font height to use for leading. It is normal if not specified. The exact normal value is implementation-dependent, but values between 100 and 120 are recommended.

fields.name: dir
fields.description: The text-direction attribute is used to adjust and override the Unicode bidirectional text algorithm, similar to the Directionality data category in the W3C Internationalization Tag Set recommendation. The default value is ltr. This attribute is typically used by applications that store text in left-to-right visual order rather than logical order. Such applications can use the lro value to better communicate with other applications that more fully support bidirectional text.

fields.name: enclosure
fields.description: Formatting of an enclosure around text or symbols.

fields.name: page
fields.description: Specifies the page number where the <credit> should appear. This is an integer value that starts with 1 for the first page. Its value is 1 if not specified. Since credits occur before the music, these page numbers do not refer to the page numbering specified by the <print> element's page-number attribute.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Specifies the exact Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) accidental character, using its SMuFL canonical glyph name.

fields.name: reference
fields.description: If the reference attribute is yes, this indicates editorial information that is for display only and should not affect playback. For instance, a modern edition of older music may set reference="yes" on the attributes containing the music's original clef, key, and time signature. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates whether the editorial information applies to the start of a series of symbols, the end of a series of symbols, or a single symbol. It is single if not specified for compatibility with earlier MusicXML versions.

fields.name: parentheses
fields.description: Specifies whether or not parentheses are put around a symbol for an editorial indication. If not specified, it is left to application defaults.

fields.name: bracket
fields.description: Specifies whether or not brackets are put around a symbol for an editorial indication. If not specified, it is left to application defaults.

fields.name: size
fields.description: Specifies the symbol size to use for an editorial indication. If not specified, it is left to application defaults.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates the start or stop of the <part-group>.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes overlapping and nested <part-group> elements, not a sequence of <part-group> elements. The default value is 1.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Refers to a <score-instrument> id attribute.

fields.name: id
fields.description: An identifier for this <score-instrument> that is unique to this document.

fields.name: id
fields.description: An identifier for this <player> that is unique within this document.

fields.name: port
fields.description: A number from 1 to 16 that can be used with the unofficial MIDI 1.0 port (or cable) meta event.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Refers to the <score-instrument> assigned to this device. If missing, the device assignment affects all <score-instrument> elements in the <score-part>.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Refers to the <score-instrument> element affected by the change.

fields.name: steal-time-previous
fields.description: The steal-time-previous attribute indicates the percentage of time to steal from the previous note for the grace note playback.

fields.name: steal-time-following
fields.description: Indicates the percentage of time to steal from the following note for the grace note playback, as for appoggiaturas.

fields.name: make-time
fields.description: Indicates to make time, not steal time, for grace note playback. The units are in real-time divisions for the grace note.

fields.name: slash
fields.description: The value is yes for slashed grace notes and no if no slash is present.

fields.name: measure
fields.description: If yes, this indicates this is a complete measure rest.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the tie.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Indicates which particular times to apply a <tie> element through a repeated section.

fields.name: id
fields.description: An IDREF back to the <score-instrument> id attribute.

fields.name: size
fields.description: Indicates full, cue, grace-cue, or large size. If not specified, the value is full for regular notes, grace-cue for notes that contain both <grace> and <cue> elements, and cue for notes that contain either a <cue> or a <grace> element, but not both.

fields.name: placement
fields.description: Indicates whether something is above or below another element, such as a note or a notation.

fields.name: cautionary
fields.description: If yes, indicates that this is a cautionary accidental. The value is no if not present.

fields.name: editorial
fields.description: If yes, indicates that this is an editorial accidental. The value is no if not present.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: References a specific Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) accidental glyph. This is used both with the other accidental value and for disambiguating cases where a single MusicXML accidental value could be represented by multiple SMuFL glyphs.

fields.name: default-x
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default horizontal position. The origin is changed relative to the start of the entire current measure, at either the left barline or the start of the system. Positive x is right and negative x is left. This value is considered to have adjusted the musical position within the measure for all descendant elements.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the <offset> element. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both features should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: default-y
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default vertical position. The origin is changed relative to the top line of the staff. Positive y is up and negative y is down.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the placement attribute. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both attributes should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: relative-x
fields.description: Changes the horizontal position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-x attribute.  Positive x is right and negative x is left. It should be interpreted in the context of the <offset> element or directive attribute if those are present.

fields.name: relative-y
fields.description: Changes the vertical position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-y attribute. Positive y is up and negative y is down. It should be interpreted in the context of the placement attribute if that is present.

fields.name: filled
fields.description: Changes the appearance of enclosed shapes from the default of hollow for half notes and longer, and filled otherwise.

fields.name: parentheses
fields.description: If yes, the notehead is parenthesized. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Indicates a particular Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) character using its canonical glyph name. Sometimes this is a formatting choice, and sometimes this is a refinement of the semantic meaning of an element.

fields.name: number
fields.description:
Indicates eighth note through 1024th note beams using number values 1 thru 8 respectively. The default value is 1.

Note that this attribute does not distinguish sets of beams that overlap, as it does for <slur> and other elements. Beaming groups are distinguished by being in different voices, and/or the presence or absence of <grace> and <cue> elements.

fields.name: repeater
fields.description: Deprecated as of Version 3.0. Formerly used for tremolos, it needs to be specified with a "yes" value for each <beam> using it.

fields.name: fan
fields.description: Beams that have a begin value may also have a fan attribute to indicate accelerandos and ritardandos using fanned beams. The fan attribute may also be used with a continue value if the fanning direction changes on that note. The value is none if not specified.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of a tie, or if this is a tie indicating that an instrument should be undamped.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Rarely needed to disambiguate ties, since note pitches will usually suffice. It is available for use in more complex tied notation situations.

fields.name: line-type
fields.description: Specifies if the line is solid, dashed, dotted, or wavy.

fields.name: dash-length
fields.description: The length of dashes in a dashed line. Ignored if the corresponding line-type attribute is not dashed.

fields.name: space-length
fields.description: The length of spaces in a dashed line. Ignored if the corresponding line-type attribute is not dashed.

fields.name: orientation
fields.description: Indicates whether slurs and ties are overhand (tips down) or underhand (tips up). This is distinct from the placement attribute used by any notation type.

fields.name: bezier-x
fields.description: The horizontal position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs and ties with a start type, or of an incoming bezier point for slurs and ties with types of stop or continue.

fields.name: bezier-y
fields.description: The vertical position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs and ties with a start type, or of an incoming bezier point for slurs and ties with types of stop or continue.

fields.name: bezier-x2
fields.description: The horizontal position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs with a continue type. Not valid for other types.

fields.name: bezier-y2
fields.description: The vertical position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs with a continue type. Not valid for other types.

fields.name: bezier-offset
fields.description: The horizontal position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs and ties with a start type, or of an incoming bezier point for slurs and ties with types of stop or continue. If both the bezier-x and bezier-offset attributes are present, the bezier-x attribute takes priority. This attribute is deprecated as of MusicXML 3.1.

fields.name: bezier-offset2
fields.description: The horizontal position of an outgoing bezier point for slurs with a continue type. Not valid for other types. If both the bezier-x2 and bezier-offset2 attributes are present, the bezier-x2 attribute takes priority. This attribute is deprecated as of MusicXML 3.1.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the slur.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple slurs when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the tuplet.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes nested tuplets.

fields.name: bracket
fields.description: Indicates the presence of a bracket. If unspecified, the result is implementation-dependent.

fields.name: show-number
fields.description: Used to display either the number of actual notes, the number of both actual and normal notes, or neither. It is actual if not specified.

fields.name: show-type
fields.description: Used to display either the actual type, both the actual and normal types, or neither. It is none if not specified.

fields.name: line-shape
fields.description: Is the line straight or curved?

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the glissando.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple glissandos when they overlap in MusicXML document order. The default value is 1.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the slide.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple slides when they overlap in MusicXML document order. The default value is 1.

fields.name: accelerate
fields.description: Does the bend accelerate during playback? Default is "no".

fields.name: beats
fields.description: The number of discrete elements (like MIDI pitch bends) used to represent a continuous bend or slide. Default is 4.

fields.name: first-beat
fields.description: The percentage of the duration for starting a bend. Default is 25.

fields.name: last-beat
fields.description: The percentage of the duration for ending a bend. Default is 75.

fields.name: start-note
fields.description: The starting note for playback, relative to the current note. It is upper if not specified.

fields.name: trill-step
fields.description: The alternating note for playback, relative to the current note. It is whole if not specified.

fields.name: two-note-turn
fields.description: Specifies the two-note turn included at the end of the trill, if any. It is none if not specified.

fields.name: accelerate
fields.description: If yes, the trill accelerates during playback. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: beats
fields.description: The number of distinct notes during playback, counting the starting note but not the two-note turn. It is 4 if not specified.

fields.name: second-beat
fields.description: The percentage of the way through the duration for landing on the second beat. It is 25 if not specified.

fields.name: last-beat
fields.description: The percentage of the way through the duration for landing on the last beat. It is 75 if not specified.

fields.name: slash
fields.description: If yes, then a vertical line is used to slash the turn. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the wavy line. The value should be continue whenever used within a <barline> element.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple wavy lines when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Specifies a particular wavy line glyph from the Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) Multi-segment lines range.

fields.name: long
fields.description: Specifies if the ornament is longer than usual. The value is no if not specified.

fields.name: approach
fields.description: Used for compound ornaments, indicating how the beginning of the ornament look relative to the main part of the mordent.

fields.name: departure
fields.description: Used for compound ornaments, indicating how the ending of the ornament look relative to the main part of the mordent.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Single-note tremolos use single, double-note tremolos use start or stop, and unmeasured tremolos use unmeasured. The default value is single for compatibility with Version 1.1.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: References a specific Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) accidental glyph. This is used both with the other accidental value and for disambiguating cases where a single MusicXML accidental value could be represented by multiple SMuFL glyphs.

fields.name: substitution
fields.description: Indicates that this fingering is a substitution in the middle of a note. It is no if not present.

fields.name: alternate
fields.description: Indicates that this is an alternate fingering. It is no if not present.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the hammer-on.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple hammer-ons when they overlap in MusicXML document order. The default value is 1.

fields.name: offset
fields.description: Specifies where the release starts in terms of divisions relative to the current note.

fields.name: shape
fields.description: Distinguishes between the angled bend symbols commonly used in standard notation and the curved bend symbols commonly used in both tablature and standard notation.

fields.name: hand
fields.description: Specifies the symbol to use If the element is empty. It is ignored if the tap glyph is already specified by the element content. If neither element content nor the hand attribute are present, the display is application-specific.

fields.name: substitution
fields.description: Indicates that this is a substitution in the middle of a note. It is no if not present.

fields.name: location
fields.description: Indicates which portion of the hole is filled in when the element value is half.

fields.name: location
fields.description: Indicates which portion of the symbol is filled in when the element value is half.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if the point of the accent is down or up. The default value is up.

fields.name: line-length
fields.description: Distinguishes between different line lengths for doit, falloff, plop, and scoop articulations.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The type describes whether a fermata is upright or inverted. It is upright if not specified.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Used to distinguish between two simultaneous chords arpeggiated separately (different numbers) or together (same number).

fields.name: direction
fields.description: Used if there is an arrow on the arpeggio sign. By default, arpeggios go from the lowest to highest note.

fields.name: unbroken
fields.description: If yes, indicates that the arpeggio continues onto another staff within the part. This serves as a hint to applications and is not required for cross-staff arpeggios.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates whether this is the top or bottom of the symbol.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Used to distinguish between two simultaneous chords bracketed separately (different numbers) or together (same number).

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is a single-note notation, or the start or stop of a multi-note notation.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple notations when they overlap in MusicXML document order. The default value is 1.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Used to specify the elision symbol to use if the element text content is empty. It is ignored otherwise.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the extension. Before Version 3.0 this attribute was not available, and an <extend> element was always treated as the start of the extension.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Specifies the lyric line when multiple lines are present.

fields.name: name
fields.description: Indicates the name of the lyric type. Common examples are verse and chorus.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Specifies which lyrics are to be sung which times through a repeated section.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates the type of playback to which the element content applies.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Refers to a specific <score-instrument> to which this playback applies.

fields.name: type
fields.description: If yes, the note should be assessed; if no, it should not be assessed. If not specified, it is no for notes with a <cue> child element and yes otherwise.

fields.name: player
fields.description: Restricts the type to apply to a single player. If missing, the type applies to all players. It references the id attribute of a <player> element defined within the matching <score-part>.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Restricts the type to apply to a set of times through a repeated section. If missing, the type applies all times through the repeated section.

fields.name: player
fields.description: Restricts the <wait> to apply to a single player.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Restricts the <wait> to apply to a set of times through a repeated section.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates the type of listening to which the element content applies.

fields.name: player
fields.description: Restricts the element to apply to a single player.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Restrict the element to apply to a set of times through a repeated section.

fields.name: default-x
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default horizontal position. The origin is changed relative to the start of the entire current measure, at either the left barline or the start of the system. Positive x is right and negative x is left.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the <offset> element. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both features should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: default-y
fields.description:
Changes the computation of the default vertical position. The origin is changed relative to the top line of the staff. Positive y is up and negative y is down.

This attribute provides higher-resolution positioning data than the placement attribute. Applications reading a MusicXML file that can understand both attributes should generally rely on this attribute for its greater accuracy.

fields.name: relative-x
fields.description: Changes the horizontal position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-x attribute.  Positive x is right and negative x is left. It should be interpreted in the context of the <offset> element or directive attribute if those are present.

fields.name: relative-y
fields.description: Changes the vertical position relative to the default position, either as computed by the individual program, or as overridden by the default-y attribute. Positive y is up and negative y is down. It should be interpreted in the context of the placement attribute if that is present.

fields.name: print-dot
fields.description: Controls the printing of an augmentation dot separately from the rest of the note or rest. This is especially useful for notes that overlap in different voices, or for chord sheets that contain lyrics and chords but no melody. If print-object is set to no, this attribute is also interpreted as being set to no if not present.

fields.name: print-spacing
fields.description: Controls whether or not spacing is left for an invisible note or object. It is used only if no note, dot, or lyric is being printed. The value is yes (leave spacing) if not specified.

fields.name: print-lyric
fields.description: Controls the printing of a lyric separately from the rest of the note or rest. This is especially useful for notes that overlap in different voices, or for chord sheets that contain lyrics and chords but no melody. If print-object is set to no, this attribute is also interpreted as being set to no if not present.

fields.name: print-leger
fields.description: Indicates whether leger lines are printed. Notes without leger lines are used to indicate indeterminate high and low notes. It is yes if not present unless print-object is set to no. This attribute is ignored for rests.

fields.name: dynamics
fields.description: Corresponds to MIDI 1.0's Note On velocity, expressed in terms of percentage of the default forte value (90 for MIDI 1.0).

fields.name: end-dynamics
fields.description: Corresponds to MIDI 1.0's Note Off velocity, expressed in terms of percentage of the default forte value (90 for MIDI 1.0).

fields.name: attack
fields.description: Alters the starting time of the note from when it would otherwise occur based on the flow of durations - information that is specific to a performance. It is expressed in terms of divisions, either positive or negative. A <note> that stops a tie should not have an attack attribute. The attack and release attributes are independent of each other. The attack attribute only changes the starting time of a note.

fields.name: release
fields.description: Alters the stopping time of the note from when it would otherwise occur based on the flow of durations - information that is specific to a performance. It is expressed in terms of divisions, either positive or negative. A <note> that starts a tie should not have a release attribute. The attack and release attributes are independent of each other. The release attribute only changes the stopping time of a note.

fields.name: time-only
fields.description: Shows which times to play the note during a repeated section.

fields.name: pizzicato
fields.description: Used when just this note is sounded pizzicato, vs. the <pizzicato> element which changes overall playback between pizzicato and arco.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Specifies the exact Standard Music Font Layout (SMuFL) coda character used for the coda sign, using its SMuFL canonical glyph name.

fields.name: type
fields.description: The value is crescendo for the start of a wedge that is closed at the left side, diminuendo for the start of a wedge that is closed on the right side, and stop for the end of a wedge.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple wedges when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: spread
fields.description: Indicates the gap between the top and bottom of the wedge as measured in tenths. Ignored if specified at the start of a crescendo wedge or the end of a diminuendo wedge.

fields.name: niente
fields.description: A value is yes indicates that a circle appears at the point of the wedge, indicating a crescendo from nothing or diminuendo to nothing. It is no if not specified, and used only when the type is crescendo, or the type is stop for a wedge that began with a diminuendo type.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the dashes.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple dashes when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the bracket.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple brackets when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: line-end
fields.description: Specifies if there is a jog up or down (or both), an arrow, or nothing at the start or end of the bracket.

fields.name: end-length
fields.description: Specifies the length of the jog if the line-end attribute is up or down.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Distinguishes different types of pedal directions.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple pedals when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: line
fields.description: If yes, then pedal lines are used.

fields.name: sign
fields.description: If yes, then Ped, Sost, and * signs are used. For compatibility with older versions, it is yes if not specified if the line attribute is no, and is no if not specified if the line attribute is yes. If no, the alignment attributes are ignored.

fields.name: abbreviated
fields.description: Used only when the sign attribute is yes and the type is start or sostenuto; otherwise it is ignored. If yes, the short P and S signs are used. If no, the full Ped and Sost signs are used. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Indicates eighth note through 1024th note beams using number values 1 thru 8 respectively. The default value is 1.

fields.name: parentheses
fields.description: Indicates whether or not to put the metronome mark in parentheses. It is no if not specified.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start, stop, or continuation of the octave shift. The start is specified as a shift up or down from their performed values

fields.name: number
fields.description: Distinguishes multiple octave shifts when they overlap in MusicXML document order.

fields.name: size
fields.description: 8 indicates one octave; 15 indicates two octaves; 22 indicates 3 octaves. The default value is 8.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Specifies if the string mute is going on or off.

fields.name: string
fields.description: Strings are numbered from high to low.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Indicates if this is the start or stop of the principal voice.

fields.name: symbol
fields.description: Indicates the type of symbol used at the start of the principal voice. When used for analysis separate from any printed score markings, this attribute should be set to none.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Distinguishes different SMuFL glyphs for wind chimes in the Chimes pictograms range, including those made of materials other than glass.

fields.name: smufl
fields.description: Distinguishes different SMuFL glyphs for a particular pictogram within the Tuned mallet percussion pictograms range.

fields.name: tip
fields.description: Indicates the direction in which the tip of the beater points.

fields.name: tip
fields.description: Represents the direction in which the tip of a stick or beater points, using Unicode arrow terminology.

fields.name: parentheses
fields.description: Indicates the presence of parentheses around the round beater part of a pictogram. The value is no if not specified.

fields.name: dashed-circle
fields.description: Indicates the presence of a dashed circle around the round beater part of a pictogram. The value is no if not specified.

fields.name: type
fields.description: Specifies the type of staff division symbol.

fields.name: sound
fields.description: The offset affects the visual appearance of the direction. If the sound attribute is yes, then the offset affects playback and listening too. If it is no, then any <sound> or <listening> associated with the <direction> takes effect at the current location. It is no if not specified for compatibility with earlier MusicXML versions.

fields.name: id
fields.description: Refers to the <score-instrument> affected by the change.

fields.name: tempo
fields.description: Tempo is expressed in quarter notes per minute. If 0, the sound-generating program should prompt the user at the time of compiling a sound (MIDI) file.

fields.name: dynamics
fields.description: Dynamics (or MIDI velocity) are expressed as a percentage of the default forte value (90 for MIDI 1.0).

fields.name: dacapo
fields.description:
Indicates to go back to the beginning of the movement. When used it always has the value "yes".

By default, a dacapo attribute indicates that the jump should occur the first time through. The times that jumps occur can be changed by using the time-only attribute.

fields.name: segno
fields.description: Indicates the end point for a backward jump to a segno sign. If there are multiple jumps, the value of these parameters can be used to name and distinguish them.

fields.name: dalsegno
fields.description:
Indicates the starting point for a backward jump to a segno sign. If there are multiple jumps, the value of these parameters can be used to name and distinguish them.

By default, a dalsegno attribute indicates that the jump should occur the first time through. The times that jumps occur can be changed by using the time-only attribute.

fields.name: coda
fields.description: Indicates the end point for a forward jump to a coda sign. If there are multiple jumps, the value of these parameters can be used to name and distinguish them.

fields.name: tocoda
fields.description:
Indicates the starting point for a forward jump to a coda sign. If there are multiple jumps, the value of these parameters can be used to name and distinguish them.
